            . I am a <rs id="t18320517-149-viclabel871" type="occupation">gun-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-149-victim1255 t18320517-149-viclabel871"></join>. I was at a <placeName id="t18320517-149-crimeloc872">skittle-ground in Bethnal-green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320517-149-crimeloc872" type="placeName" value="skittle-ground in Bethnal-green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320517-149-crimeloc872" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-149-off869 t18320517-149-crimeloc872"></join>, on the 19th of April, from dinner time till half-past four o'clock, next door to my own house; I had a light blue coat on, with a velvet collar - I took it off, and hung it on the pales between the two yards - I saw the prisoner there, with a black coat on; I missed my coat in about ten minutes or a quarter of an hour, and he was gone - I have never seen it since; I had seen the prisoner before.</p>
               <p>JANE HITCHINS. My husband keeps the house. I saw the prisoner pass my bar with two coats on, a blue one undermost, and an old black one over it - they were both close bodies coats: I saw him come in with only one coat.</p>
               <p>THOMAS MORFORD (Police-constable K 83.) I took the prisoner with an old dark blue coat on, with coloured buttons - it had a silk collar, not a velvet collar.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I put on two coats, as it was a wet day, and I had not been long out of a fever.</p>
